# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: don-kelly-baseball
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2001-major-league-baseball-draft] The **2001 Major League Baseball draft**, was held on June 5 and 6.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2001-major-league-baseball-draft] Pick from Chicago White Sox as compensation for signing of free agent Sandy Alomar Jr.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2001-major-league-baseball-draft] On June 1, 2001, Rolando Viera, a Cuban baseball pitcher who had recently left Cuba, attempted to enjoin Major League Baseball from including him in the 2001 draft so that he could instead sign as a free agent.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2001-major-league-baseball-draft] Viera, represented by attorney Alan Gura and agent Joe Kehoskie, claimed that the MLB draft was discriminatory because it had different signing rules for Cubans than for other foreign players.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2001-major-league-baseball-draft] Whittemore ruled that whatever financial loss Viera suffered from being subject to the draft did not satisfy the federal injunction requirement of irreparable harm.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2001-major-league-baseball-draft] Viera was picked by the Boston Red Sox that same week in the seventh round of the draft.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2001-major-league-baseball-draft] Paul, MN native Joe Mauer with the number one pick in the 2001 draft.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2001-major-league-baseball-draft] The 18-year-old Mauer, a catcher from Cretin-Derham Hall High School in St.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2001-major-league-baseball-draft] Paul, became the seventh Minnesotan to be selected in the first round and the first to be chosen number one overall.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2001-major-league-baseball-draft] The back-stop was a member of the USA Junior National Team and won a gold medal at the world tournament in Taiwan in 1999.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2001-major-league-baseball-draft] He was also a High School football standout as a quarterback and signed a letter of intent to play football at Florida State University before being drafted.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2001-major-league-baseball-draft] Right-handed pitcher Mark Prior of the University of Southern California was selected by the Chicago Cubs with the second overall pick in the draft.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2001-major-league-baseball-draft] Prior, who was previously selected in the supplemental first round of the 1998 draft by the Yankees, was the first college player chosen in the 2001 draft.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2001-major-league-baseball-draft] Prior won numerous National Player of the Year awards after going 15–1 with a 1.69 ERA and 202 strikeouts to lead the Trojans to a College World Series berth in his junior year.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] The **2007 Major League Baseball season** began on April 1 with a rematch of the 2006 National League Championship Series; the St.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals and New York Mets played the first game of the season at Busch Stadium in St.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] Louis, Missouri, which was won by the Mets, 6–1.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] The season ended on October 28, with the Boston Red Sox sweeping the World Series over the Rockies, four games to zero.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] A special exhibition game known as the "Civil Rights Game" was played on March 31 in AutoZone Park in Memphis, Tennessee, between the Cardinals and the Cleveland Indians to celebrate the history of civil rights in the United States.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] The 2007 season commemorates the 60th anniversary of Jackie Robinson's entry into the game, breaking the color barrier.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] For the fourth consecutive season, MLB regular season attendance increased by comparison with the previous year.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] Note: Two teams in the same division could not meet in the division series.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] The 3–2 pitch with one out and nobody on base was hit at 8:51 PM US PDT and according to hittrackeronline.com was estimated to have gone 422 feet.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] However, the Nationals came back and won the game, 8–6.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] Through his final home game (and last game of the season), on September 26, Bonds has hit 762 home runs.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] The baseball that was hit for the record was caught by Mets fan Matt Murphy, who put the ball up for auction online.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] The winning bidder was fashion designer Marc Ecko, who purchased the baseball for $752,467 (US) and let fans decide what to do with it in an internet poll.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] Options included donating the ball to the Baseball Hall of Fame as-is, donating it marked with an asterisk (reflecting the widely held belief that Bonds used performance-enhancing drugs to break the record), or sending the baseball into space.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] The vote decided that an asterisk would be added, and the ball donated to Cooperstown.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] In an interview that aired on MSNBC's *Countdown with Keith Olbermann* on November 1 and 2, Bonds stated to interviewer Jim Gray that if the ball were to be put on display with the asterisk, he would boycott his own Hall of Fame induction if he were elected.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] Three no-hitters were pitched during the 2007 regular season.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] This is the most in a single season since the three pitched in 2001.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] All three no-hitters in 2007 were in the American League, which is the most in a single league since the record-tying 1991 season when the two leagues combined for seven no-hitters (4 AL, 3 NL).
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] On July 10, 2007, at AT&T Park in San Francisco, the American League defeated the National League by a score of 5–4.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] The victory was the tenth consecutive (excluding the 2002 tie) for the AL, and their eleven-game unbeaten streak matches only the NL's streak from 1972 to 1982 in All-Star history.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] On April 15, Major League Baseball celebrated the sixtieth anniversary of the debut of Jackie Robinson at Ebbets Field in Brooklyn, breaking the color barrier.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] Cincinnati Reds outfielder Ken Griffey Jr. asked Robinson's widow, Rachel, and commissioner Bud Selig for permission to wear Robinson's number 42 in honor of him.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] He was granted permission, and Selig later said that any player who wanted to wear number 42 on his jersey could.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] The jersey was worn without the players' name on the back, as was the case when Robinson played with the Brooklyn Dodgers.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] All jerseys that were worn were auctioned off with all the proceeds donated to the Jackie Robinson Foundation, an organization which awards scholarships to African-American high school graduates to further themselves in colleges academically.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] The Dodgers, Cardinals, and Brewers elected to have the entire team wear number 42 in his honor.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] The Pittsburgh Pirates, Phillies, and Astros were also scheduled to share that honor, but their games were postponed due to rain.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] The Phillies and Astros honored Robinson on April 23 when they made up their postponed game as originally planned, while the Pirates waited until April 27 to honor Robinson by wearing #42 as a team against the Reds.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] On August 10, the Cleveland Indians paid tribute to Larry Doby, the first African-American to play in the American League at Jacobs Field in Cleveland, Ohio.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] Every player on the Indians wore number 14, the number Doby wore during his career with the Indians.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] The Nationals played their final game at Robert F.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] Kennedy Stadium on September 23, beating the Phillies 5–3.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] The team's new home, Nationals Park, formally opened on March 30, 2008.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] The Tampa Bay franchise played its last season as the Devil Rays.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] In 2008, the name was shortened to Tampa Bay Rays.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] during the 2007 season, and became the first player to be called out in the same play that they got their 3000th hit.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] He was tagged out while trying to stretch his hit into a double.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] He announced his retirement on July 24, about a month after achieving the milestone.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] He finished his career with 668 doubles, good for 5th all-time at the time he retired.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] , playing the position for the first time in 15 years.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] Conine, then of the New York Mets, announced his retirement on September 20, right before their last road trip to visit the Florida Marlins.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] The Marlins, fans of which refer to him as "Mr.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] Ironically, losses to the Marlins contributed to the Mets failing to make the playoffs.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] Josh Hancock, a relief pitcher with the St.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals, died on April 29 in a car accident outside St.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] The 29-year-old pitcher was killed within a couple of minutes after impact when the SUV he was driving crashed into a towing vehicle on Interstate 64.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] This marks the second time in five years that a Cardinals pitcher lost his life before a game, the other being Darryl Kile, who died suddenly on June 22, 2002.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] The team postponed their game scheduled for later that day against the Chicago Cubs to pay respect to Hancock.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] A police report revealed that Hancock was intoxicated at the time of his fatal accident with a blood-alcohol level of 0.157, nearly double the legal limit in Missouri.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] Police also found 8.55 grams of marijuana along with a glass smoking pipe in his vehicle, although toxicology tests later proved no drugs were in his system except alcohol.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] In addition, Hancock was talking on a cell phone when the accident occurred and was not wearing a seatbelt.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] An accident reconstruction team determined that Hancock was driving 68 mph in a 55 mph zone.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first season of Fox's new media agreement lasting through 2013.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] *Fox Saturday Baseball* expanded to the entire 26 weeks of the regular season, up from 18 under the previous contract.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] Fox also retained exclusive rights to televise the World Series and the All-Star Game.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] Fox would also get exclusive rights to televise the American League Championship Series in odd-numbered years, and the National League Championship Series in even-number years.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] TBS also signed a deal lasting through 2013, As part of the contract, TBS relinquished its rights to air Atlanta Braves games nationally after the 2007 season, by separating WTBS (now WPCH) channel 17 from the TBS network, eventually rebranding as *Peachtree TV* on October 1, 2007.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] TBS also gained exclusive broadcast rights to the Division Series in both leagues, any tiebreaking games, the National League Championship Series in odd-numbered years, and the American League Championship Series in even-number years.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] Additionally, TBS gained the rights to a Sunday afternoon *Game of the Week* beginning in 2008.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2007-major-league-baseball-season] ESPN continued to televise games on Sunday nights, Wednesday nights, and other weeknights, but no longer any postseason games.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] The **2009 Major League Baseball season** began on April 5, 2009; the regular season was extended two days for a one-game playoff between the Detroit Tigers and the Minnesota Twins for the American League Central title.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] The postseason began the next day with the Division Series.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] The World Series began on October 28, and ended on November 4, with the New York Yankees defeating the Philadelphia Phillies in six games.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] This was the second time the season was completed in November.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] The only other occasion was the 2001 World Series, because of the delaying of the end of that season due to the September 11 attacks as November baseball would be guaranteed when Game 4 was played on Sunday, November 1.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] Had the 2009 World Series gone the full seven games, Game 7 would've been played on November 5, the latest date ever scheduled for a World Series game.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] It became the latest date for a World Series game in 2022.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] The American League champion had home field advantage for the World Series by virtue of winning the All-Star Game on July 14 at Busch Stadium in St.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] In addition, the annual Civil Rights Game became a regular season game, and was played June 20 at Great American Ball Park in Cincinnati, Ohio, when the host Cincinnati Reds lost to the Chicago White Sox in an interleague game, 10–8.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] Both teams wore replicas of their 1965 uniforms in the contest.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] The Seattle Mariners named Milwaukee Brewers scouting director Jack Zduriencik its new general manager on October 22, replacing interim GM Lee Pelekoudas.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] Washington Nationals GM Jim Bowden resigned on March 1 amid allegations that he was skimming bonus money from Latin American players.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] Team president Stan Kasten first took over the bulk of his duties before transferring them to assistant GM Mike Rizzo, who had served as acting GM, and was named as the full-time general manager on August 20.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] During the last days of the regular season, two teams fired their general managers, effective at the end of the season.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] On October 3, the Toronto Blue Jays fired J.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] The following day, the San Diego Padres axed Kevin Towers, who had been the longest-tenured GM in Major League Baseball at 14 seasons.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] Cito Gaston and Jerry Manuel both entered their first full season as managers of the Toronto Blue Jays and New York Mets, respectively, after taking over for managers dismissed in the middle of the 2008 season.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] Gaston had previously been the Blue Jays' manager from 1989 until 1997.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] On January 15, the owners of the 30 Major League Baseball clubs approved two rule changes governing the playing of postseason and one-game playoff games.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] The 2009 season marked the opening of two new stadiums, both in New York City; Citi Field for the Mets and the new Yankee Stadium for the Yankees.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] They respectively replaced Shea Stadium (which was dismantled during the 2008–09 offseason) and the original Yankee Stadium (which became a public park after its demolition).
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] Because of the smaller seating capacities in these new parks, Dodger Stadium is now the largest capacity park in use with 56,000 seats, and is also the third oldest ballpark in Major League Baseball behind Fenway Park and Wrigley Field.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] Citi Field opened with a night game on April 13 as the Mets hosted the San Diego Padres losing 6–5.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] In that game, Jody Gerut of the Padres became the first player in major league history to open a new ballpark with a leadoff homer.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] Three days later, the Cleveland Indians inaugurated New Yankee Stadium against the Bronx Bombers.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] On Jackie Robinson Day (April 15), a rotunda at Citi Field was named in honor of Jackie Robinson and was dedicated prior to the Mets–Padres game that day.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] The 2009 season also marked the final season of the Hubert H.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] Humphrey Metrodome as the home for the Minnesota Twins, where they had played since 1982.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] In 2010, the team moved to Target Field, their new baseball-only stadium located a short distance across town.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] Previously, since moving from Washington, D.C. in 1961, the franchise has shared, first Metropolitan Stadium, and then the Metrodome with the NFL's Minnesota Vikings; they also shared tenant rights at the Metrodome with the University of Minnesota's football team.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] The Golden Gophers started to play on-campus at TCF Bank Stadium in 2009.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] The Metrodome's last scheduled regular season game was to be played on Sunday, October 4, 2009, but the Twins tied the Detroit Tigers necessitating a one-game playoff between the two teams on October 6.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] While not a new stadium, Kansas City's Kauffman Stadium completed a two-year renovation.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] The first year saw a new video board dubbed "Crown Vision" and refitting of several sections.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] Improvements for 2009 include a new glass and brick facade to the exterior of the ballpark, newly expanded team Hall of Fame, a new sports bar/restaurant, improved sightlines, new luxury suites and refurbished press and radio/TV facilities to name a few.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] In late March, the Florida Marlins had their funding for a new stadium at the former site of the Miami Orange Bowl approved by Miami-Dade County commissioners.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] Groundbreaking ceremonies were held on July 18, with an opening by 2012, at which time the team will be renamed the **Miami Marlins**.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] This would have marked the first full season in the US for baseball games to be telecast as the transition from analog to digital television that was to have been made on February 17.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] However, the transition took place June 12.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] MLB was the last of the four major team sports to start its own television channel.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] In Canada, Toronto Blue Jays games will be televised on Rogers Sportsnet and TSN.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] RSN also holds the Canadian rights to air the Fox and ESPN/ESPN2 games if they do not conflict with Blue Jays games, as well as the All-Star Game and the entire postseason.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] In Australia free to air channel One HD shows up to 5 games live per week, and European channel ESPN America broadcasts games as well.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] ESPN Radio served as MLB's national radio network, broadcasting *Sunday Night Baseball* as well as selected Saturday and holiday games during the regular season, the Home Run Derby and All-Star Game, and all postseason series.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] As stated earlier, the Mets and Yankees wore patches commemorating the inaugural seasons of their new parks, the Twins wore patches commemorating their final season at the Metrodome, and the Cardinals, hosting the All-Star Game, wore a patch to celebrate that event.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] The Pittsburgh Pirates, Detroit Tigers, Oakland Athletics and Chicago White Sox led the Majors in wearing throwback uniforms.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] On May 2 at Safeco Field, the Athletics and Seattle Mariners honored 1939 by wearing special uniforms.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] The Mariners honored the Seattle Rainiers and the Oakland Athletics honored the Oakland Oaks from that season.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] Both teams played in the Pacific Coast League that season.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] The A's then wore a 1980s styled uniform in St.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] Petersburg on July 11 against the Tampa Bay Rays, who wore uniforms from their inaugural season of 1998 when they were known as the "Devil Rays".
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] Finally, On August 16, the Athletics and White Sox used vintage throwbacks.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] The A's wore uniforms from their Philadelphia period, with blue caps and a large A on the front of their jerseys.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] The White Sox wore their jerseys with a large S with a lowercase O in the top loop and a lowercase X in the bottom loop.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] On June 14, the Tigers and Pirates wore throwback uniforms to commemorate the 100th anniversary of both Forbes Field and the 1909 World Series between the two teams.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] That game also featured a throwback atmosphere: no music or flashy graphics, no mascots (meaning no Jolly Roger or Pirate Parrot), and a hand-operated scoreboard.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] One modern item occurred in the pre-game: The Stanley Cup champion Pittsburgh Penguins made a surprise visit and brought the trophy with them.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] The Pirates and the Kansas City Royals also honored the Negro leagues on June 26 and 27 with the Pirates wearing the Homestead Grays uniforms and the Royals donning Kansas City Monarchs replicas.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] The Pirates and the Cincinnati Reds recreated their 1979 National League Championship Series uniforms on August 21 as part of the Buccos' 30th anniversary celebration of their World Series championship.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] The Bucs wore their gold pillbox hat with a gold jersey and black pants, a faux pas from the uniforms that season as a black cap was worn that year with the gold jersey.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2009-major-league-baseball-season] The Tigers and the Cleveland Indians played in Negro league replicas twice, with the Tigers in Detroit Stars uniforms, and the Indians outfitted in Cleveland Buckeyes replicas.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] The **2011 American League Division Series** (abbreviated **ALDS**) were two best-of-five playoffs comprising the opening round of Major League Baseball’s (MLB) 2011 postseason, played to determine the participating teams in the 2011 American League Championship Series.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] Three divisional winners and a fourth team—a wild card—played in two series.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] TBS televised all games but the Game 2's of both series in the United States.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] The Game 2's of both series were aired on TNT due to schedule conflicts with other ALDS games or the NLDS.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] The regular season finished on September 28, with the ALDS beginning September 30.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] Game 5 of the Yankees–Tigers series was played on October 6.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] Under MLB's playoff format, no two teams from the same division were matched up in the Division Series, regardless of whether their records would normally indicate such a matchup.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] Home field advantage went to the team with the better regular-season record with the exception of the wild card team, which defers home field advantage regardless of record.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] This was the second consecutive playoff meeting between the Rangers and Rays; the Rangers won 3–2 in the 2010 ALDS.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] The Tigers and Yankees previously met in the 2006 ALDS, in which the Tigers won 3–1, the last time they reached the postseason.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] The Rangers would go on to defeat the Tigers in the ALCS, then lose the 2011 World Series to the National League champion St.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] † Game suspended in the bottom of the second inning due to rain; official MLB records and statistics all carry the original game date.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] In front of a Yankee Stadium record setting crowd of 50,940, Justin Verlander, 24-game winner, Triple Crown winner, and Cy Young Award frontrunner, started Game 1 for the Tigers against Yankees' ace CC Sabathia.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] The Tigers started the scoring on Delmon Young's two-out solo home run in the top of the first inning.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] The Yankees managed to tie the game in the bottom half without a hit.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] Leadoff batter Derek Jeter reached first base on a wild pitch third strike.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] Jeter moved to third on Curtis Granderson's walk and Robinson Canó's groundout and then scored on Alex Rodriguez's RBI groundout.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] The game was delayed by rain in the middle of the second inning and later suspended and resumed at 8:37 p.m. on October 1, pushing Game 2 back to October 2.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] The suspension significantly altered both teams' pitching rotations for the series.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] Doug Fister and Iván Nova, both of whom were originally scheduled to start Game 2, entered as relief pitchers when Game 1 was resumed.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] Jorge Posada led off the continuation of the game with a single and then Russell Martin doubled, but Posada was tagged out trying to go home on a Brett Gardner grounder.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] The Tigers threatened in the fifth inning, putting men on first and second.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] However, Granderson made a strong throw to Jeter, who relayed to Martin at home to tag out Alex Avila trying to score the go-ahead run.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] Granderson hit a double in the bottom of the inning and Canó drove him in with an RBI double that was reviewed by instant replay after the ball hit the top of the wall near the boundary line.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] In the next inning, the Yankees scored six runs and, after Fister was relieved, a Canó grand slam, extending the Yankees lead to 8–1.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] Later, Canó knocked in his sixth RBI on an eighth-inning double to score Jeter, tying a Yankees postseason record for RBIs in a game by a single player.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] The Tigers threatened in the top of ninth when Delmon Young's single, Miguel Cabrera's walk, and Víctor Martínez' single loaded the bases.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] Nova was relieved by Luis Ayala, who surrendered an RBI groundout by Avila, an RBI single by Ryan Raburn, and a single by Jhonny Peralta to load the bases again.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] The Yankees turned to their closer, all-time saves leader Mariano Rivera, in a non-save situation, who struck out Wilson Betemit to end the game.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] Max Scherzer threw 5+1⁄3 no-hit innings before allowing a single to Robinson Canó.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] Scherzer got help from the Tigers' offense early, as Magglio Ordóñez singled with one out in the first inning, then Miguel Cabrera hit an opposite-field home run one out later to put the Tigers in front 2–0.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] In the sixth, Austin Jackson reached on Derek Jeter's throwing error to first, then Ordóñez singled.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] After Delmon Young struck out, back-to-back RBI singles from both Cabrera and Víctor Martínez made it 4-0 Tigers and knocked Freddy García out of the game.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] The Yankees got on the board in the eighth on Curtis Granderson's leadoff home run off of Joaquín Benoit, but in the ninth, Luis Ayala hit Brandon Inge with a pitch.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] Inge moved to second on a groundout and scored on Don Kelly's single to give the Tigers the run back.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] In the bottom of the inning, Nick Swisher hit a leadoff home run off José Valverde, who then allowed a triple to Jorge Posada and walked Russell Martin before Andruw Jones's sacrifice fly cut the Tigers' lead to 5–3.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] Jeter struck out and Granderson walked before Valverde retired Robinson Canó on a groundout, sending the teams to Detroit with the series tied at a game apiece.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] In a rematch of the Game 1 starters, the Yankees struck first off of Justin Verlander when Derek Jeter singled to lead off the first and scored on Curtis Granderson's triple.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] After Robinson Cano struck out, Granderson scored on Alex Rodriguez's single to make it 2–0 Yankees.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] In the bottom of the third, Ramon Santiago's RBI single with two on off of C.C.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] Sabathia scored Brandon Inge from second.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] A single loaded the bases before Miguel Cabrera grounded into a double play, but Austin Jackson scored to tie the game.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] Inge hit a leadoff single, moved to second on a sacrifice bunt, and scored again on an RBI double by Santiago in the fifth inning, giving the Tigers the lead.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] Don Kelly hit a leadoff single and scored on an RBI double by Jhonny Peralta in the sixth to increase Detroit's lead.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] After Alex Avila's sacrifice bunt, Sabathia was relieved by Rafael Soriano.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] In the seventh, after getting two outs, Verlander walked Jorge Posada and hit Russell Martin with a pitch before both men scored on a Brett Gardner RBI double, tying the game.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] In the bottom of the inning, Delmon Young's home run off of Soriano put the Tigers back in front 5–4.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] José Valverde recorded his 50th consecutive save in as many tries—including regular season—for the Tigers win, striking out Jeter with runners on first and second, both having reached on walks, to end the game.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] With their backs against the wall, the Yankees relied on A.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] Burnett, who was assigned to the bullpen in the Division Series due to inconsistency, re-took the starting role thanks to the suspension in Game 1.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] Burnett was almost to be relieved by Cory Wade in the bottom of the first inning after issuing a two-out walk to Víctor Martínez that loaded the bases, but Curtis Granderson's run-saving catch helped Burnett escape the jam unharmed.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] Derek Jeter's two-run double in the third put the Yankees on board, but Martínez's solo homer in the bottom of the fourth cut the Yankees' lead to one.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] Granderson's RBI double and Alex Rodriguez's sacrifice fly in the fifth increased the lead to three.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] Burnett was relieved after Don Kelly's two-out single in the bottom of the sixth, and he gave the Yankees what they were hoping for—tossing 5+2⁄3 innings, allowing four hits, one earned run, and four walks while striking out three.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] Later, Granderson's second run-saving catch of the day ended the sixth inning for Burnett and the Yankees.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] The Yankees' offense erupted in the top of the eighth.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] Three struggling Yankees hitters—Rodriguez, Mark Teixeira, and Nick Swisher—hit consecutive singles to start the eighth inning.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] A balk by the Tigers' reliever Al Alburquerque and an RBI single by pinch-hitter Jesús Montero brought in two more runs for the Yankees.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] Russell Martin was walked to load the bases again, followed by Brett Gardner's RBI single for another run.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] The next two batters—Derek Jeter and Granderson—both struck out, but Montero scored on a wild pitch by Tigers' reliever Daniel Schlereth during Granderson's at-bat.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] Robinson Canó singled in two more runs to increase the lead to 10–1.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] The six-run rally was more than enough for the Yankees, as the Yankees' relievers—Rafael Soriano, Phil Hughes, and Boone Logan—held the Tigers hitless in the remaining 3+1⁄3 innings while striking out six.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] Game 5 was a rematch of the two pitchers of record in Game 1—Iván Nova and Doug Fister.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] Despite the fans setting another Yankee Stadium record with 50,960 in attendance, the Tigers eliminated the Yankees with a 3–2 win.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] Back–to–back homers by Don Kelly and Delmon Young in the first inning put Detroit on top.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] Young's homer was his third, a Tigers record in a playoff series.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] Nova did not last long, as he was pulled after the second inning with forearm tightness.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] The Tigers made it 3–0 in the top of the fifth when Víctor Martínez singled off CC Sabathia to drive in Austin Jackson.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] In the bottom of the fifth the Yankees finally scored on a Robinson Canó solo homer, and got another run in the seventh when Mark Teixeira walked with the bases loaded to score Derek Jeter.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] However, Joaquín Benoit managed to strike out Nick Swisher with the bases still loaded, ending the threat.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] José Valverde closed the door when he struck out Alex Rodriguez in the ninth, earning his 51st straight save of the combined 2011 season and postseason.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] The Tigers became only the third team to beat the Yankees in consecutive post-season series meetings; previously the 1921–22 New York Giants and the 2002 and 2005 Angels were able to beat the Yankees in consecutive playoff series meetings.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] This was also the first time since 2007 the Yankees were eliminated at home.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] CC Sabathia appeared in relief for the first time in his career when he relieved Boone Logan in the fifth, in which he surrendered the winning run.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] Mariano Rivera made what would be his final postseason appearance, pitching a scoreless ninth.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] The Rays were coming off of their incredible momentum from their late September rally to steal the Wild Card spot from the Red Sox, while the Rangers were looking to win their second straight AL pennant.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] Rookie Matt Moore started Game 1 for the Rays, his second Major League start and fourth appearance since his September 12 promotion from Triple-A.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] Moore gave the Rays seven shutout innings—allowing two hits and two walks while striking out six.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] Wilson hit Ben Zobrist with a pitch leading off the second, then Johnny Damon's home run put Tampa up 2−0.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] Kelly Shoppach then singled, moved to second on a ground out, and scored on Matt Joyce's single.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] Shoppach's three-run home run after two singles next inning made it 6−0 Tampa.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] In the fifth, Adrián Beltré's throwing error to first allowed Damon to reach base, then Shoppach's second home run of the game made it 8−0 Tampa.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] They added one more run in the ninth on Damon's single with runners on second and third off of Mike Gonzalez.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] Wade Davis retired the Rangers in order in the bottom half to preserve the shutout.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] The Rays struck first on Kelly Shoppach's bases-loaded walk in the first inning and Matt Joyce's two-run home run in the fourth.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] However, Rays starter James Shields ran into trouble in the bottom of the fourth.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] After Elvis Andrus' hit-by-pitch and consecutive singles by Josh Hamilton and Michael Young loaded the bases, Shields again hit Adrián Beltré and surrendered a two-run single to Mike Napoli.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] The next two batters, Nelson Cruz and David Murphy, both struck out, but Murphy reached first base on an uncaught third strike thanks to a wild pitch earlier to advance the runners.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] Mitch Moreland followed up with an RBI groundout to score Napoli.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] The five-run fourth gave the Rangers a 5–3 lead over the Rays.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] Rangers starter Derek Holland put another zero on the scoreboard before handing the game to the bullpen.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] The Rangers continued to score on Ian Kinsler's two-run double in the sixth.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] Evan Longoria came up with a three-run homer in the seventh to bring the Rays within a run.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] Moreland answered with a solo homer in the eighth to increase the lead to two.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] Neftalí Feliz pitched a scoreless ninth to record the save.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] Until 2023, this was the only ALDS game the Rangers had won at home, and with the Rangers moving to Globe Life Field in 2020, the only ALDS game the Rangers won at Globe Life Park.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] A Desmond Jennings home run in the fourth gave the Rays an early lead.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] David Price, winless against the Rangers in his Major League career, held Texas without a run for six innings before giving up a Mike Napoli two-run homer after Adrián Beltré singled.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] Josh Hamilton later hit a two-RBI single off reliever J.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] Later, in the bottom half, Sean Rodriguez hit an RBI groundout to score Johnny Damon and cut Texas's lead to two.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] In the bottom of the eighth, Jennings cut the deficit to one on his second solo home run of the game; however, the Rays' comeback attempt was put to rest on a double play grounder by Kelly Shoppach in the ninth.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] The Rangers struck first with an Ian Kinsler home run off Rays' starter Jeremy Hellickson in the first inning.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] Three homers by Adrián Beltré off Hellickson in the second and fourth, and off Matt Moore in the seventh gave Texas the much-needed cushion.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] The Rays tried to come back when Matt Joyce doubled in the second and scored Sean Rodriguez in a plate collision with Mike Napoli.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] Later Rodriguez also scored in the fourth and ninth off Casey Kotchman RBI singles, but the game ended after Joyce popped out in foul territory to Beltré and Desmond Jennings grounded into a force out.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] Beltré became the sixth player in MLB history to hit three home runs in a single postseason game, joining Babe Ruth (1926 and 1928 World Series), Bob Robertson (1971 NLCS), Reggie Jackson (1977 World Series), George Brett (1978 ALCS), and Adam Kennedy (2002 ALCS).
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] With the win, the Rangers advanced to their second straight ALCS.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2011-american-league-division-series] This also marked the Rangers' fifth straight postseason win at Tropicana Field.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] The **2012 American League Division Series** were two best-of-five-game series in Major League Baseball’s (MLB) 2012 postseason to determine the participating teams in the 2012 American League Championship Series.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] The three divisional winners and a fourth team—the winner of a one-game Wild Card playoff— played in two series.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] TBS carried most of the games, with some on MLB Network or TNT.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] The series used the 2–3 format for 2012 because on March 2 the league had implemented the new "wild card" playoff, eliminating the travel day between Games 4 and 5.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] The 2–3 format was used for best-of-five Championship Series rounds prior to 1985 and for the Division Series rounds from 1995 to 1997.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] This was the third postseason match-up between the Athletics and the Tigers, and previously the Tigers had defeated the A's 4–0 in the 2006 ALCS.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] The Yankees and Orioles were meeting in the postseason for the second time; the Yankees had beaten the Orioles 4–1 in the 1996 ALCS, which witnessed the controversial Jeffrey Maier incident in Game 1.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] The Tigers went on to defeat the Yankees in the ALCS, then lose the 2012 World Series to the National League champion San Francisco Giants.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] The Yankees struck first in the first inning off of Jason Hammel when Derek Jeter singled and Ichiro Suzuki doubled to score Jeter for the game's first run, giving the Yankees a 1–0 lead.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] In the bottom of the third inning, Orioles outfielder Chris Davis singled, followed by a Lew Ford single, a Robert Andino sacrifice bunt, and a single by Nate McLouth, to give the O's a 2–1 lead.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Then in the top of the fourth, the Yankees tied the game at two with a Mark Teixeira single with two men on.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] The game remained tied going into the ninth inning, until a lead-off home run by Russell Martin off of Jim Johnson pushed the Yankees ahead 3–2.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Consecutive singles by Raúl Ibañez, Derek Jeter, and Ichiro Suzuki scored Ibanez, giving the Yankees a 4–2 lead.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Robinson Canó doubled to score Jeter and Suzuki.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Tommy Hunter relieved Johnson and Nick Swisher hit a sacrifice fly to score Canó, making the score 7–2.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Sabathia pitched 8+2⁄3 innings and after allowing a two-out double to Lew Ford, David Robertson came in to get the final out of the game, giving the Yankees the win and a one-game-to-nothing lead.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] The Game 2 pitching matchup was a sharp contrast, pitting postseason veteran Andy Pettitte against rookie Wei-Yin Chen.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Similar to the first game, both Jeter and Suzuki would reach base.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] With two men on and nobody out, Alex Rodriguez hit a sinking line drive which was speared in the air by Robert Andino, who then doubled up Derek Jeter off second.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Later in the inning, Robinson Canó ripped a double down the right field line, and Ichiro Suzuki masterfully avoided the tag of Matt Wieters to score, giving the Yankees an early 1–0 lead.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] It was all for naught, however, as Pettitte allowed the Orioles to load the bases with two outs on two singles and a walk, then gave up a two-run single to Chris Davis in the third inning.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Baltimore tacked on some insurance in the sixth on a Mark Reynolds single.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] The Yankees threatened in the seventh when Jeter hit a single to make it 3–2.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] New York had players on second and third with two out in that inning, but Nick Swisher flied out to end the inning.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Jim Johnson got the save to send the series to the Bronx tied at one game apiece.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Baltimore had a 2–1 lead going into the ninth inning behind a strong performance by Miguel González.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Rookies Ryan Flaherty and Manny Machado became the first pair of rookies to ever homer for the same team in the same game.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Machado's blast ranked him as the second youngest player in postseason history, behind the Yankees' own Andruw Jones who had done so against the Yankees while with the Atlanta Braves in the 1996 World Series.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Machado also became the youngest nine-hole hitter to homer in a postseason game at 20 years, 96 days.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Flaherty's home run in the third off of Hiroki Kuroda put the Orioles up 1–0 before the Yankees tied the score in the bottom half when Russell Martin doubled with one out and scored on Derek Jeter's triple.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Machado's home run in the fifth put Baltimore up 2–1.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Heading to the ninth inning and three outs away from a 2–1 series deficit, the Yankees sent up Raúl Ibañez to pinch-hit for a struggling Alex Rodriguez with one out.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Ibañez then lined a home run into the right field seats off Orioles closer Jim Johnson to tie the game in the ninth inning.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Then in the 12th inning, Ibañez crushed the first pitch of the inning into the second deck of Yankee Stadium to win the game and take a series lead in walk-off fashion.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Ibanez's heroics in this game marked the second time in eight days that he provided the game tying and walk-off hits for the Yankees.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] During a game against the Red Sox on October 2, 2012, Ibanez hit a game-tying 2-run home run off Andrew Bailey in the 9th inning, and then hit a walk-off single off of Andrew Miller in the 12th.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] At age 40, Ibañez set at least four MLB postseason records with his two home runs.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Joe Saunders and Phil Hughes matched zeroes for four innings, before Nate McLouth led off the fifth for Baltimore with a home run.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] The Yankees responded in the sixth when Robinson Canó had an RBI groundout, but they left a runner in scoring position in that inning when Alex Rodriguez struck out.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Rodriguez also left men on second and third with one out in the bottom of the eighth, dropping his batting average for the series down to .125 and continuing to draw the scorn of Yankees fans.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] The game remained tied until the 13th inning, when Manny Machado hit a leadoff double off of David Phelps, then scored on an RBI double to J.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Jim Johnson got his second save of the series, ensuring a deciding Game 5 the next day.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] This was the third time a postseason series had back-to-back games going at least 12 innings, joining the 1986 NLCS and the 2004 ALCS.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] This was the final game in Jim Thome's Hall of Fame career.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] The Yankees clinched a trip to the ALCS for the third time in four years with a 3–1 win.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] CC Sabathia gave the Yankees his second big performance of the series, pitching a complete game, giving up one run on four hits while striking out nine.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] The only nervous moments came in the sixth, when a long fly ball by Nate McLouth was ruled foul and the eighth, when the Orioles loaded the bases with one out, but Sabathia got out of the jam by striking out McLouth and getting J.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] The Yankees scored first in the fifth, when Game 3 hero Raúl Ibañez singled to score Mark Teixeira, who singled and stole second off of Jason Hammel.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] The Yankees tacked on some insurance in the sixth, when Derek Jeter walked with an out and scored on an Ichiro Suzuki double, and followed up in the seventh with a Curtis Granderson home run.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] It proved enough, as the Orioles only scored one run in the eighth on a Lew Ford single with two on.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Sabathia got Matt Wieters to ground out for the final out, sending the Yankees to play for the pennant versus the Detroit Tigers.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Sabathia was the first Yankee pitcher to pitch a complete game in the postseason since Roger Clemens pitched one against the Seattle Mariners in Game 4 of the 2000 ALCS.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Coco Crisp led off the game with a home run on Justin Verlander's fourth pitch, a 1–2 fastball.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Verlander threw 26 pitches in the first inning, but he managed to only allow one run.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] The lead did not last long, as Austin Jackson doubled to lead off the bottom of the first, and moved to third on an infield hit by Quintin Berry.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Miguel Cabrera followed with a double play grounder, with Jackson scoring on the play.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] In the bottom of the third, with the game tied at one, Quintin Berry hit a slow ground ball up the first-base line.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] A's starter Jarrod Parker fielded the ball, but it rolled out of his glove for an error.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] That allowed Omar Infante, who doubled earlier in the inning, to score from second base and give the Tigers a 2–1 lead.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Alex Avila led off the fifth inning with a first-pitch homer to extend the Detroit lead to 3–1.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] In the top of the seventh, Verlander struck out Derek Norris to tie a playoff career-high in strikeouts with 11, which he set the prior year in Game 3 of the ALDS against the Yankees, which he won.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] In the bottom of the seventh, with two runners on, Pat Neshek, pitching for the first time since the death of his one-day-old son, got out of the jam by getting Infante to ground into a force out and striking out Austin Jackson.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] In the top of the eighth, Brandon Moss came close to a game-tying two-run home run off Joaquín Benoit, but fell just short when the ball held up at the right-field wall for Andy Dirks, who made the catch.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] José Valverde pitched a scoreless ninth inning for his first save of the 2012 postseason.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] He struck out two and got George Kottaras to pop up to end the game.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Oakland took a 1–0 lead in the top of the third inning when they put together three singles off Tiger starter Doug Fister, with Yoenis Céspedes' base hit driving in the game's first run.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Brandon Moss followed with another single, but Tiger right fielder Avisaíl García threw out Coco Crisp at home plate as Crisp was attempting to score from second base.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] The Tigers tied the score at one in the bottom of the third.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Miguel Cabrera hit his second double of the game, moved to third on a single by Prince Fielder, and scored on a slow roller to first off the bat of Delmon Young.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Oakland retook the lead in the seventh inning when an RBI single by Cliff Pennington plated Seth Smith, but the lead was short-lived.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] In the bottom of the frame, Austin Jackson and Omar Infante each hit two-out singles.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Miguel Cabrera followed with a short fly ball to center field, which a hard-charging Coco Crisp bobbled and dropped.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Jackson and Infante both scored on the error, and the Tigers had their first lead of the game, 3–2.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Detroit reliever Joaquín Benoit, however, failed to hold the lead in the next inning.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Yoenis Cespedes singled and stole both second and third.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] With one out and the infield in, Benoit threw a wild pitch that scored Cespedes to tie the game at three.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Josh Reddick then quickly untied it one batter later, with a home run to right.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] For the third time in the game, and fourth time in the series, the A's failed to hold a lead in the bottom of an inning that they had gained in the top of the same inning.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Delmon Young greeted reliever Ryan Cook with a single, and was lifted for pinch runner Don Kelly.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Jhonny Peralta followed with a single, sending Kelly to second.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Kelly and pinch runner Danny Worth then moved up 90 feet (27 m) on a sacrifice bunt by Andy Dirks.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Kelly scored on a Cook wild pitch, knotting the game at four.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] A's closer Grant Balfour was called upon in the ninth to keep the game tied, but could not succeed.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] After back-to-back one-out singles by Omar Infante and Miguel Cabrera, Prince Fielder was intentionally walked, bringing Don Kelly to the plate.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Kelly, a .186 hitter during the regular season, delighted the home crowd by hitting a walk-off sacrifice fly to right that plated Infante with the winning run.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Al Alburquerque got the win in relief, while Balfour took the loss.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Returning home to Oakland, the A's took a 1–0 lead for the third time in the series, but this time it would not be relinquished.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Coco Crisp led off the first inning with a single, and moved to second on a walk to Stephen Drew.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Yoenis Céspedes followed with an RBI single to center that scored Crisp.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Tiger starter Aníbal Sánchez avoided further damage by striking out Brandon Moss and getting Josh Reddick to ground into an inning-ending double play.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] The A's scored one more time off Sánchez when Seth Smith hit a homer in the fifth, giving the A's a 2–0 lead.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] That was all the scoring in this game, as the Tiger hitters could manage only four hits and no runs off starter Brett Anderson and three relievers.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Grant Balfour redeemed himself from Game 2 by closing the door on the Tigers in the ninth for his first save of the series.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] The A's turned in several fine defensive plays as well, highlighted by Coco Crisp's over-the-wall catch in center field on a potential home run off the bat of Prince Fielder.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Fielder was victimized later by Yoenis Céspedes, who robbed the Tiger first baseman of extra bases with a diving catch of a line drive in left-center.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] For the first time in the series, the Tigers took the first lead of the game.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] In the top of the third inning, Alex Avila doubled off A's starter A.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Griffin, took third on a sacrifice bunt by Omar Infante, and scored on a single by Austin Jackson.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Prince Fielder made it 2–0 in the fourth with a home run.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] The A's got one run back in the bottom of the sixth, scoring an unearned run off Tiger starter Max Scherzer.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Coco Crisp, who had reached on a Prince Fielder error and advanced to second on a wild pitch, scored on a double by Stephen Drew.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Drew, however, was thrown out trying to stretch the hit into a triple.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] The Tigers got the run back in the top of the eighth.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Omar Infante singled, advanced to second on a sacrifice bunt by Austin Jackson, and scored on a single by Avisaíl García.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Tiger closer José Valverde was called upon in the ninth to protect the 3–1 lead, the same lead he had when earning the save in Game 1.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] But the A's greeted Valverde with three straight hits.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] A single by Josh Reddick and a double by Josh Donaldson were followed by a two-run double off the bat of Seth Smith that tied the game at three.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] It looked like the game might go into extra innings after Valverde got a pop out and a strikeout, but the A's—who had a league-leading 14 walk-off wins during the regular season—were not done.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Coco Crisp hit a two-out, game-winning single to score Smith, sending the home crowd into a wild victory celebration.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] With the series on the line, the teams turned to their Game 1 starters—Justin Verlander for the Tigers and Jarrod Parker for the A's.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] As he had done so many times after a Tiger loss over the last few seasons, Verlander was the Tigers' stopper.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] The 2011 Cy Young and MVP winner allowed just four hits and a walk in a complete-game shutout, and only one Oakland baserunner made it as far as second base (Josh Donaldson in the eighth).
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Verlander also struck out 11 batters for the second time in the series, giving him an ALDS record of 22 K's.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] The Tiger batters did all of their scoring in just two innings.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Omar Infante led off the third inning with a single, advanced to second on a wild pitch, and scored on an Austin Jackson double.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Jackson advanced to third on a sacrifice bunt by Quintin Berry and scored on Parker's second wild pitch of the inning.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] In the top of the seventh, Jhonny Peralta led off with a single and stole second.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] One out later, Omar Infante singled to send Peralta to third, and Austin Jackson knocked in Peralta with a single off A's reliever Ryan Cook.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Quintin Berry drew a walk to load the bases before Cook hit Miguel Cabrera with an 0–2 pitch to force in the Tigers' fourth run of the game.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] Prince Fielder followed with a run-scoring single off reliever Jerry Blevins, and Stephen Drew's error on a hard grounder by Delmon Young allowed Berry to score the sixth and final run of the game.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] The Tigers would move on to the ALCS for the second straight season.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] This series was an inversion of the 1972 American League Championship Series between the same clubs.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2012-american-league-division-series] In that series. the Athletics won the first two games at Oakland, the Tigers won the next two at Detroit, but the Athletics won the deciding Game 5 2–1 at Tiger Stadium.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2014-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The **2014 Major League Baseball season** began on March 22 at the Sydney Cricket Ground in Sydney, Australia, between the Los Angeles Dodgers and the Arizona Diamondbacks.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2014-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The North American part of the season started on March 30 and ended on September 28.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2014-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Major League Baseball All-Star Game's 85th edition was held on July 14 at Target Field in Minneapolis, Minnesota, home of the Minnesota Twins.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2014-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The American League (AL) beat the National League (NL) 5–3.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2014-major-league-baseball-season-p01] With the win, the AL champion earned home-field advantage during the World Series.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2014-major-league-baseball-season-p01] This year the Houston Astros hosted the Civil Rights Game on May 30 at Minute Maid Park.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2014-major-league-baseball-season-p01] They played host to the Baltimore Orioles.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2014-major-league-baseball-season-p01] This was also the final season of Bud Selig as the Commissioner of Baseball.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2014-major-league-baseball-season-p01] Selig served as the Executive Council Chairman from 1992 to 1998, acting as the commissioner, and then was appointed as the official commissioner in 1998.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2014-major-league-baseball-season-p01] On August 14, 2014, the franchise owners selected Rob Manfred to become the new Commissioner, starting in 2015.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2014-major-league-baseball-season-p01] No significant changes were made to the 2014 schedule.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2014-major-league-baseball-season-p01] As was the case in 2013, each team played 19 games against each division opponent for a total of 76 games, and six or seven games against each team from the other two divisions in its league for a total of 66 games.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2014-major-league-baseball-season-p01] All teams played 20 interleague games, with the majority of match-ups following the divisional rotation in place since 2004.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2014-major-league-baseball-season-p01] Teams played four games against a designated "rival" in two back-to-back two-game series, one home and one away.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2014-major-league-baseball-season-p01] Unlike in 2013, when all of these series were played during the same week, these rivalry series were spread from early May through mid-August.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2014-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The table below shows the interleague rivals for the 2014 season.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2014-major-league-baseball-season-p01] On August 15, 2013, Major League Baseball announced that it would expand its video review process for the 2014 season, and MLB clubs unanimously approved the new rules on January 16, 2014.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2014-major-league-baseball-season-p01] Managers were now able to challenge certain plays no more than twice per game, including force plays, fair or foul balls, and batters hit by a pitch, among others.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2014-major-league-baseball-season-p01] If a manager exhausted his ability to challenge plays during the game and after the beginning of the seventh inning, the umpire crew chief could choose to invoke instant replay on any reviewable call.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2014-major-league-baseball-season-p01] Calls that were challenged were reviewed by an umpiring crew at MLB headquarters in New York City, which made the final ruling.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2014-major-league-baseball-season-p01] On December 11, 2013, the Playing Rules Committee voted overwhelmingly to outlaw home-plate collisions between runners and catchers.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2014-major-league-baseball-season-p01] On February 24, 2014, the new rule was put into effect as Rule 7.13 was released.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2014-major-league-baseball-season-p01] At the end of the 2013 season, the following teams made replacements to their managers.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2014-major-league-baseball-season-p02] This was the first year of the new eight-year television contracts with ESPN, Fox Sports, and TBS.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2014-major-league-baseball-season-p02] ESPN aired Sunday night games, some Monday Night games and Wednesday night games, while Fox Sports aired Saturday games and TBS aired Sunday games.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2014-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Contract provisions in ESPN's contract virtually eliminated local blackouts among the network's Monday and Wednesday night games, allowing ESPN coverage to co-exist with that of the local broadcasters in home markets.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2014-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Sunday Night Baseball blackout rules still applied.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2014-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Fox Sports' contract also covered Fox Sports 1, which began its first year of Major League Baseball coverage.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2014-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Fox Sports 1 televised 40 regular-season games (mostly on Saturdays) and possibly up to 15 playoff games.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2014-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The increase in televised games from previous years was due to a provision in the contract that allowed for Fox Sports 1 to take a game between two teams in which Fox operated the teams' individual RSNs and elevated it into a national broadcast.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2014-major-league-baseball-season-p02] As a result, MLB regular season coverage on the Fox network was reduced to 12 weeks beginning in 2014.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2014-major-league-baseball-season-p02] In the post-season, TBS and ESPN aired two Wild Card Games.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2014-major-league-baseball-season-p02] TBS, Fox Sports 1 and MLB Network aired the Division Series, while TBS aired the American League Championship Series.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2014-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Fox network and Fox Sports 1 aired the National League Championship Series, and the Fox network exclusively aired the All-Star Game and the World Series.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2014-major-league-baseball-season-p02] This was the first year of eight-year contracts for national broadcasts in Canada.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2014-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Sportsnet, owned by Rogers Communications (and sister company of the Toronto Blue Jays), continues to be the primary rightsholder, retaining rights to the All-Star Game, the Home Run Derby, and most postseason games.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2014-major-league-baseball-season-p02] In total (including Canada-wide rights to all Blue Jays games which are acquired directly from the team), Sportsnet's various channels will carry almost 300 MLB games per season until 2021.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2014-major-league-baseball-season-p02] As part of the deal, Rogers Cable became the Canadian launch partner for MLB Network, which was not previously available in Canada, and did not secure carriage on any Canadian providers other than Rogers that year.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2014-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Despite this, MLB Network's Division Series telecasts were kept exclusive to that channel in Canada as well.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2014-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Separately, TSN announced its own eight-year deal to expand its MLB coverage.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2014-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Having carried ESPN's *Sunday Night Baseball* since 2010 under sublicense from Sportsnet, TSN and TSN2 will now carry all of ESPN's regular-season coverage (ESPN being a minority partner in TSN), adding *Monday Night Baseball* and *Wednesday Night Baseball*, totalling over 75 games per year.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2014-major-league-baseball-season-p02] French-language rights, previously held exclusively by TSN's French-language sister channels RDS and RDS2, will now be split with TVA Sports, with each group airing approximately 70 games per season (TVA Sports also carries additional Blue Jays games acquired directly from the team).
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2014-major-league-baseball-season-p02] RDS will continue to carry the All-Star Game and the World Series, but the remaining postseason rights will be split equally between RDS and TVA Sports.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2014-major-league-baseball-season-p02] ESPN Radio aired its 17th season of national coverage, including Sunday night games, Saturday games, Opening Day and holiday games, the All-Star Game and Home Run Derby, and the entire postseason.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2014-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The move to WFAN means that the New York Mets moved to WOR (purchased by Clear Channel in late 2012) for the 2014 season, as they had been on WFAN since the station had adopted the all-sports format in 1987.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2014-major-league-baseball-season-p02] This will be the final year in which the Chicago Cubs will air on WGN.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2014-major-league-baseball-season-p02] WGN has had some form of broadcast relationship with the Cubs since 1925 and has been the exclusive broadcaster of the team since 1958; for many years, the Cubs and WGN were both owned by Tribune Company.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2014-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The spin-off of the Cubs to new ownership, combined with continued financial losses, the Cubs' persistent on-field futility and the pending end of the rival Chicago White Sox's contract with WSCR after the 2015 season, prompted Tribune to end its relationship with the Cubs.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2014-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Cubs broadcasts will move to CBS Radio's WBBM for 2015 and, if the White Sox do not renew with WSCR, to WSCR for 2016 and beyond.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The **2015 Major League Baseball season** began on April 5 with a Sunday night game between the St.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] Louis Cardinals and the Chicago Cubs at Wrigley Field, and ended on November 1 with the Kansas City Royals winning the World Series.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] This was Rob Manfred's first season serving as Commissioner of Baseball.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Major League Baseball All-Star Game's 86th edition was held on Tuesday, July 14 at Great American Ball Park in Cincinnati, Ohio, home of the Cincinnati Reds.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The American League won the game 6–3, to give the American League home-field advantage in the World Series.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] As was the case in 2014, teams were scheduled to play 19 games against each division opponent for a total of 76 games, and six or seven games against each team from the other two divisions in its league for a total of 66 games.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] All teams were scheduled to play 20 interleague games throughout the season.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] For 2015, the interleague matchups were AL East vs.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] Since "natural rivalry" matchups will be part of the three-year divisional rotation (for the first time), the schedule format for interleague games was different from previous years.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] During the final day of the regular season, all games were scheduled to start simultaneously at 3:00 p.m.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] Eastern Time, reminiscent of the English Premier League's last-day "Survival Sunday" scheduling.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] MLB hoped that this would add excitement and drama during the final day, and also limit teams' ability to rest starters at the last minute based on early game results.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] At the end of the 2014 season, the following teams made replacements to their managers.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The New York Mets changed their home jersey from a cream shade to white and took away the home white alternate jersey.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Minnesota Twins took away the pinstripes from their home jersey and added a gold trim to the "Twins" wordmark.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] A hat was also added highlighting the "Twin Cities" logo in gold.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Pittsburgh Pirates introduced a new camouflage alternate jersey in honor of the U.S.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] Military which will be worn during all Thursday home games.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] A new camo-style hat also accompanies this uniform with a black bill and black "Pittsburgh" logo.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Seattle Mariners have added an alternate cream color jersey with blue and yellow, the original colors of the team from 1977–1992.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] An alternate light blue hat with a gold "Seattle" logo will accompany the uniform as well.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The San Francisco Giants have added an alternate black jersey, featuring a new alternate logo depicting the Golden Gate Bridge.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Cleveland Indians darkened the shade of navy blue in their caps and jerseys.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Astros and Angels wore 1965 uniforms on April 18 to mark the 50th anniversary of the Astrodome and the 50th anniversary of the renaming of the team to Astros.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Reds and Cubs wore 1990 uniforms on April 24 to mark the 25th anniversary of the Reds' winning the 1990 World Series.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Tigers and Indians wore Negro league throwbacks on April 25.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Tigers wore the uniforms of the Detroit Stars, while the Indians wore the uniforms of the Cleveland Buckeyes.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Red Sox wore their 1975 home uniforms on May 5 to mark the 40th anniversary of the club's 1975 AL Championship and trip to the 1975 World Series.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The uniforms had the Massachusetts bicentennial patch.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Mariners and Red Sox wore Negro league throwbacks on May 16.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Red Sox wore the uniforms of the Boston Royal Giants, and the Mariners wore the uniforms of the Seattle Steelheads.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Cubs and Royals wore 1915 Federal League throwbacks on May 31 (originally, they were supposed to have worn them on May 30, but the game was postponed due to rain).
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Cubs wore the uniforms of the Chicago Whales, while the Royals wore the uniforms of the Kansas City Packers.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Cardinals and Phillies wore 1960s throwbacks on June 19.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Cardinals wore 1961 uniforms, which did have the players' numbers on the fronts of the shirts.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Mets and Braves wore Negro league throwbacks on June 20.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Mets wore the uniforms of the Brooklyn Royal Giants, while the Braves wore the uniforms of the 1938 Atlanta Black Crackers.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Red Sox wore their 1975 road uniforms on June 27 against the Rays.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Rays, meanwhile, wore their "fauxback" jerseys, which have a retro feel yet never actually were worn regularly because the franchise did not exist back then.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Athletics wore 1965 Kansas City Athletics uniforms June 27.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] Ironically, the Kansas City Royals were their opponents.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Pirates and Brewers wore Negro league throwbacks on July 18.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Pirates wore the uniforms of the Pittsburgh Crawfords, while the Brewers wore the uniforms of the Milwaukee Bears.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Rangers and Astros wore 1980s throwbacks on July 18 as part of a 1980s night promotion at Minute Maid Park.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Cardinals and Royals wore 1985 uniforms on July 23 to mark the 30th anniversary of the 1985 World Series.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] They were supposed to be worn on June 14, but that game was postponed due to rain.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Cubs and White Sox wore 1959 uniforms on August 14 in honor of Minnie Miñoso at US Cellular Field.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] Each of the White Sox players wore Minoso's number 9.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Cubs and Tigers wore 1945 uniforms on August 19 to mark the 70th anniversary of the 1945 World Series.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The White Sox wore 1976 uniforms on August 27.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] Players, coaches, and umpires at all games wore #42 on April 15, the 68th anniversary of Jackie Robinson's debut in the majors.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Giants wore uniforms with gold "Giants" script lettering and numbering on April 18 to celebrate their 2014 World Series title.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] On April 20 (Patriots' Day), the Boston Red Sox wore home white jerseys with "BOSTON" written on the front to mark the second anniversary of the Boston Marathon bombings.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The uniform also sported the 2013 navy-blue circular patch with a white border on the left shoulder saying "B Strong" (with the red B in the classic font featured on the Red Sox's caps).
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Milwaukee Brewers wore their batting practice jerseys as an alternate on April 21.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The front has the Brewers' "M" logo on front, and has gold trim on the side.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Giants wore Spanish-language "Gigantes" uniforms on May 5, Cinco de Mayo.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Orioles wore a special uniform May 11, the first game at Camden Yards with spectators since April 26 due to the riots that took place in the city in April.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The uniforms were in their home whites, but had their road "Baltimore" script on the front instead of the usual "Orioles".
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Reds wore camouflage uniforms and caps on May 16 and June 6.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The uniforms had the "Reds" script on the front, instead of the player's number and the Reds' logo.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] All teams wore camouflage uniforms on May 25, Memorial Day in the United States.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] Although Memorial Day is not a legal holiday in Ontario, the Blue Jays wore camouflage.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Reds wore green caps and uniforms on June 19 as part of a "Shamrock the Ballpark" promotion.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] Like the camouflage uniforms, the uniforms had the "Reds" script on the front, instead of the player's number and the Reds' logo; the uniforms have a shamrock on the right sleeve, instead of the Mr.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Blue Jays wore a special uniform on Canada Day.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The uniform had the Blue Jays wordmark in red, instead of blue.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] They had the Canadian flag on their right sleeve.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Red Sox, their opponent, wore a Canadian flag on their uniform as well.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The uniform was worn again on August 30.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] All teams wore American flag-themed caps and uniforms on July 4, Independence Day in the United States.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The uniforms had an American flag on a sleeve.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The logos and players' numbers had stars on them; the caps had a star instead of a baseball on the MLB logo.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Blue Jays wore a jersey with both the U.S. and Canadian flags.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Royals and the Astros wore Spanish-language "Los Reales" and "Los Astros" uniforms on July 25.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Tigers wore Spanish-language "Tigres" uniforms August 8.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The uniforms were based on the Tigers' 1960 uniforms.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Reds and the Diamondbacks wore Spanish-language "Los Rojos" and "Los D-backs" uniforms August 21.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Mets wore camouflage uniforms on August 31.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Mariners wore Spanish-language "Marineros" uniforms on September 12.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p01] The Astros wore Spanish-language "Los Astros" uniforms on September 27.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p02] 2015 marks the second year of MLB's eight-year deal with Fox Sports, ESPN, & TBS.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Fox will televise Saturday night games for eight consecutive weeks, leading up to the All Star Game, which will also air on Fox.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Fox will then televise Saturday afternoon games for the last four weeks of the regular season.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Fox Sports 1 will televise games on Tuesday nights and Saturdays, both during the afternoon and at night.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p02] ESPN will televise games on its flagship telecast, Sunday Night Baseball, as well as Monday and Wednesday nights.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p02] TBS will televise Sunday afternoon games for the last thirteen weeks of the regular season.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Fox and ESPN Sunday Night Baseball telecasts will be exclusive; all other national telecasts will be subject to local blackout.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p02] TBS will televise the National League Wild Card Game, Division Series, and Championship Series.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p02] ESPN will televise the American League Wild Card Game, Fox Sports 1 and MLB Network will televise American League Division Series, and Fox and Fox Sports 1 will televise the American League Championship Series.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The World Series will air exclusively on Fox for the sixteenth consecutive year.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p02] All postseason games will air on ESPN Radio.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p02] 2015 was the second year of MLB's eight-year contracts for national broadcasts in Canada.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p02] As in 2014, when the two Division Series games carried by MLB Network in the U.S. was also exclusive to that channel in Canada despite very limited carriage, Game 3 of the Royals-Astros ALDS was exclusive to MLBN in both countries.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p02] However Sportsnet aired all games of the Blue Jays-Rangers ALDS in Canada (MLBN carried Game 2 in the United States).
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p02] TSN holds English-language rights to most regular season games in ESPN's U.S. package.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p02] French-language rights are split between RDS and TVA Sports.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The Chicago Cubs opted to re-negotiate their terrestrial television contracts for the 2015 season through 2019, when all the Cubs' television rights contracts will expire, including their cable deal with Comcast SportsNet Chicago.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p02] WGN-TV will still hold rights to 45 Cubs games per season, and its overflow broadcasts will move to WPWR-TV in place of WCIU-TV.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p02] WGN will be joined by ABC-owned station WLS-TV, which will now broadcast 25 games per season.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p02] The cable network WGN America will no longer carry Chicago White Sox or Chicago Cubs games, as the network has phased out Chicago sports programming as part of its transition towards becoming a nationally focused entertainment network.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p02] After an absence of over a decade, New York Yankees telecasts will return to WPIX, sharing time with the Mets after WWOR-TV gave up its contract due to the rejection of a contract extension.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p02] Both teams' games on WPIX will still be produced by the YES Network and SportsNet New York respectively.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p02] ESPN Radio aired its 18th season of national coverage, including Sunday Night Games, Saturday games, Opening Day and holiday games, the All-Star Game, and Home Run Derby, and the entire postseason.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p02] WBBM became the radio home of the Chicago Cubs starting in April 2015 after long time home WGN gave up the broadcasting rights after 90 years.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p02] WJZ-FM, for the second time, became the flagship radio station for the Baltimore Orioles.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p02] WJZ-FM held the rights for the 2009 and 2010 seasons.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/2015-major-league-baseball-season-p02] New rules were made to increase the pace of the game.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] Kelly was born in Butler, Pennsylvania, and played baseball at suburban Mt.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] Lebanon High School; in his senior year the team won the Class AAA state title.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] Lebanon, he regularly alternated between the two middle infield positions with Josh Wilson, another future Major League player.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] He was not then considered a "draftable" player and attended Point Park University, a liberal arts college in downtown Pittsburgh.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] Over three seasons he batted .413 and struck out just 20 times in over 500 at-bats.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] In the summer of 2000 Kelly played for the Petersburg Generals of the Coastal Plain League, a collegiate summer league.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] Kelly's collegiate performance prompted interest from major league teams and the Detroit Tigers drafted him in the eighth round (237th overall) of the 2001 Major League Baseball draft.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] Detroit assigned him to the Low-A Oneonta Tigers in the New York–Penn League, where he batted .286 and struck out sixteen times—second lowest in the league.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] The next year Detroit promoted him to the Single-A West Michigan Whitecaps in the Midwest League.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] Kelly was named the starting shortstop for the Eastern All-Stars in the league's mid-season All-Star game.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] Kelly's versatility was first put to the test at the professional level when he was with the High-A Lakeland Tigers in 2003.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] He shifted to third base when Anderson Hernández replaced him at shortstop.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] Kelly eventually spent more time at first and second base after Ryan Raburn took over at third.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] In 2004 Detroit invited Kelly to spring training, and in his first at-bat in a spring training game Kelly hit a home run against the Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] On March 17, Detroit optioned Kelly back to Erie, but he missed most of the season with an injured shoulder.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] Kelly returned to Erie in 2005 and picked up where he had left off, hitting .340 over 82 games.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] *Baseball America* named Kelly the best-hitting prospect in the Eastern League.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] On June 30, Detroit promoted him to the Triple-A Toledo Mud Hens of the International League, one step away from the majors.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] Kelly played in 43 games for the Mud Hens in 2005 and batted .250, a tenure partially interrupted by a groin injury.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] Commented Mud Hens manager Larry Parrish: "Hitting-wise, there's been a little bit of an adjustment for him here...He tore up Double-A, and here he's done alright.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] But it's his first year here, and he's still going through a learning process." In the off-season Kelly played for the Mesa Solar Sox of the Arizona Fall League.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] In 2006 Kelly almost made the Major League team out of spring training but instead returned to Toledo.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] Detroit manager Jim Leyland said "When push came to shove, he ran into a numbers game." At Toledo Kelly's numbers fell off; Detroit demoted him to Erie after hitting .228.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] At Erie his numbers improved to .272, but at the end of the season Detroit removed Kelly from their 40-man roster, making him a free agent.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] The Pittsburgh Pirates, Kelly's hometown team, signed him to a minor league contract on December 14, 2006.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] He made the Major League team as a utility player, filling in at second base, shortstop, and left and right field.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] His major league debut came on April 2, 2007, in a season-opening 4–2 victory over the Houston Astros at Minute Maid Park.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] As a pinch hitter for Dámaso Marte, Kelly popped out to the shortstop to end the Pirates half of the ninth inning.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] Kelly played sparingly, amassing 27 at-bats over 25 games and hitting .148, before Pittsburgh designated him for assignment on June 12 to make room for Dan Kolb.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] Kelly cleared waivers and joined the Triple-A Indianapolis Indians on June 23.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] Kelly finished out the season with Indianapolis, batting .247 and playing both shortstop and in the outfield.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] Pittsburgh granted Kelly free agency at the end of the season.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] Kelly signed a minor league contract with the Arizona Diamondbacks and spent the entire 2008 season with the Triple-A Tucson Sidewinders, where he batted .275 but never made it with the major league club and was granted free agency at the end of the season.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] In 2009, Kelly signed a minor league contract with an invitation to spring training with the Tigers.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] Following spring training Kelly rejoined the Mud Hens, with whom he had last played in 2006.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] On June 11, 2009, the Tigers called Kelly up to the Major League club to replace outfielder Clete Thomas.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] Kelly played his first game for Detroit against the Pittsburgh Pirates, his former club.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] After going hitless in his first game, he hit a two-RBI single and a double against Pittsburgh, obtaining his first major league extra base hit and RBIs.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] On October 1, 2010, Kelly hit a home run in both games of a doubleheader against the Baltimore Orioles.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] On July 24, 2011, Kelly was pranked by Justin Verlander after noticing that his right shoe was caught on fire.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] In his first two seasons with the Tigers, Kelly added first and third base and center field to the positions he has played in the majors.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] He was called on to pitch with two outs in the top of the ninth inning after manager Jim Leyland thoroughly depleted his bullpen in a 16–9 defeat to the New York Mets at Comerica Park on June 29, 2011.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] Throwing only five pitches, he used a curveball to get Scott Hairston to fly out to center field.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] Kelly was the first position player to pitch in a game for the Tigers since Shane Halter did it in October 2000.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] He reached the milestone of having played every position on the field in his major league career in a 15–3 loss at home to the San Francisco Giants three nights later on July 2.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] He entered the contest at the start of the fourth inning, replacing starting catcher Víctor Martínez who had left the game with a bruised right shoulder.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] In the decisive Game 5 of the 2011 American League Division Series against the New York Yankees, Kelly belted a first-inning solo home run off Iván Nova into the right field seats at Yankee Stadium to give the Tigers a 1–0 lead, one which they never relinquished.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] Detroit went on to win the game, 3–2, and moved on to face the Texas Rangers in the American League Championship Series.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] On August 3, 2012, Kelly was designated for assignment to make room on the 40-man roster for outfielder Andy Dirks, who returned to the Tigers after coming off the disabled list the same day.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] On August 9, 2012, Kelly cleared waivers and his contract was outrighted by Detroit to their Triple-A affiliate Toledo.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] The Tigers called him up again on September 1, and later named him to their post-season roster after the team clinched the AL Central division.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] He hit a walk-off sacrifice fly in Game 2 of Detroit's American League Division Series against the Oakland Athletics.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] On October 31, 2012, Don Kelly cleared waivers and became a free agent.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] On January 16, 2013, Kelly signed a minor league deal with the Tigers.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] He made the team out of spring training, and played another full season as the club's super-utility man.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] In 216 at-bats, Don hit .222 with six home runs and 23 RBIs, while playing six defensive positions.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] After the season, Kelly signed a one-year deal with Detroit that would pay him $1 million in 2014, avoiding arbitration.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] On November 3, 2014, Kelly declined his minor league assignment and became a free agent.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] On January 18, 2015, Kelly signed a minor league contract with the Miami Marlins.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] After hitting .270 with two doubles and five RBI with .681 OPS in Spring training, the Marlins purchased Kelly's contract and placed him on the Opening Roster.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] Kelly suffered a fractured finger early in the 2015 season and was placed on the 15-day disabled list on April 13.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] Kelly had two at-bats before getting hurt and was 0-for-2.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] On July 18, 2015, the Marlins announced that Kelly would have season-ending Tommy John surgery.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] On February 3, 2016, Kelly re-signed with the Marlins to a minor league deal with an invitation to spring training.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] He was released by the Marlins on March 29 and re-signed the next day.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] Kelly was called up from New Orleans on July 6.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] With the return of Dee Gordon to the Marlins roster after an 80-day suspension for PED use, Kelly was designated for assignment on July 28, 2016.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] On February 18, 2017, Kelly was named a scout and assistant on the player development staff for the Detroit Tigers organization.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] On September 29, Kelly was promoted to a Major League scout for the Tigers.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] On November 21, 2018, Kelly was named the Houston Astros' first base coach.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] Kelly was named the Pittsburgh Pirates' bench coach on December 7, 2019.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] On May 8, 2025, Kelly was named manager of the Pirates following the firing of Derek Shelton.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] On September 29, 2025, Kelly and the Pirates agreed to a contract extension.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] Kelly spends his offseasons in Mars, Pennsylvania, with his wife, Carrie, and their three sons, Brett, Luke and Brooks.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] He married Carrie Walker on January 13, 2007; his brothers-in-law include former major league infielder Neil Walker and former minor leaguer Matt Walker; his father-in-law is former major league pitcher Tom Walker.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] His wife Carrie was a women’s basketball player at Wagner College and the Northeast Conference Rookie of the Year in 2001.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] She went on to play a year of professional basketball for Killarney (St.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] Paul’s) of the Irish Women’s SuperLeague.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] His sister Ashlee was a standout women's basketball player for Quinnipiac University and the Northeast Conference Player of the Year in 2003.
[src:don-kelly-baseball/don-kelly-baseball] After spending three years as head women's basketball coach at Mercy College, she was named assistant coach at Iona College on July 1, 2009.
